description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/meshtastic/codec.c:567-600

  static int write_user(uint8_t *buf, size_t buflen, size_t *pos,
                const struct lichen_meshtastic_local_info *info)
  {
      char id[10];
      uint32_t node_num = info_node_num(info);

      id[0] = '!';
      for (size_t i = 0U; i < 8U; i++) {
          uint8_t nibble = (uint8_t)((node_num >> ((7U - i) * 4U)) & 0x0fU);
          id[i + 1U] = (char)(nibble < 10U ? '0' + nibble : 'a' + (nibble - 10));
      }
      id[9] = '\0';

The node_num is converted to hex without checking if info_node_num returned a valid value. info_node_num defaults to 0x4c494348U if node_num is 0, so there's always a value.

However, if node_num were somehow invalid (e.g., containing non-printable characters after conversion... wait, hex is always printable).

Actually this is fine - the hex conversion is safe. False alarm.

But worth noting: no validation that node_num won't produce a Meshtastic-reserved ID range.
